thing, seeping from the altar to her Lord, from the ancient, slick worn stones of the room, from the softly snickering minions of Hatred arrayed about the room, bound in service to those who stood there. Most of all, however, it poured forth from the coarse quilted fabric that heated her to dripping, and protected the inky velvet of her skin from the blooded, patched bronze encasing her body. It was a glorious smell. <br>
<br>
The suit was a gift from another knight, one of the few that had taken a liking to her during her apprenticeship. It had, or so the story said, been ripped most violently from a wood elven woman who forgot that even the mightiest warrior must fall before the touch of Innoruuk. The weight of the great blade strapped to her back gave her comfort and courage as she listened to the dry, gravelly voice of her Lord on Norrath, Nezzka Tolax.<br>
<br>
&quot;Girl, you have proven yourself to be a knight of Innoruuk, both in word and deed. It is time for your final testing. When this is done, you will be a woman grown, and a knight new made. Are you prepared?&quot;<br>
<br>
The woman spent a moment steeling herself against what was to come, and then nodded, speaking the ritual words, in a feverishly fervent tone... &quot;I am prepared. May the fires of Innoruuk's Hatred and thine strip my soul, and temper it in his eternal service.&quot; And then she fell to one knee, the stiff plates of bronze jabbing against her waist and legs.<br>
<br>
The elder knight reached downwards, to place his hand on her forehead, in a manner curiously like that of the benediction of a High Elven cleric, a ritual that was once theirs until the traitorous will of the all Mother made itself known to thier Father. &quot;The will of the Father be done.&quot; And with that, the knights hand began to blaze with the power of Innoruuk, the ultimate power channeled through a mortal vessel well prepared to accept it, and into the woman.<br>
<br>
Her body failed her will then, though her voice did not, the woman jerking back from the wave of agony sweeping through her body, her back arching and legs failing under unimaginable pain. She crumpled to the floor, blood trickling from the corner of her mouth, threatening to choke off her ragged gasps of breath, her body shrieking in pain...<br>
<br>
&quot;She lives. Amazing.&quot; The whisper floated from the corner of the room, from the awed lips of a true priest of Innoruuk, and Lord of the Dead. The clerics did the work of the Father, but all knew that it was the Lords and Knights of the Dead that spoke for Him. And to gain this, each shown to Hell by thier earthly master, to gaze upon His face and know His will, before the clerics returned the soul to the body. <br>
<br>
The simple response from the Lord Knight was delivered in the same, flat, gravelly tone as he always spoke in. &quot;A Reaver then. It has occured before. Do not infuse her with life.&quot; <br>
<br>
But for her, there was no response, her mind shrieking in many times the suffering of her body. The cool touch of the stone through her armor was lost to her, as she spasmed in pain, her soul being reworked by the power of her Dark Lord, hatred and bitter agony coursing through her heart, all directed at the All Mother. Tunare's creations were nothing, suitable for cattle and slaves, to be ground under when able, simply ignored when not. The Goddess herself was to be her prey.<br>
<br>
And so, as the waves of her Father's power passed her, she stood, her body unsteady at first, but soon recovering, gaining it's life back swiftly.. and she spoke the words of the ancient ritual, words spoken only by those powerful enough to survive the touch of the Prince of Hate. &quot;I am a Reaver of Innoruuk, and a vessel of his will. This ye shall know, and accept. His hatred shall become my blade and my armor, and the will of Tunare shall shatter upon me as a wave upon a great wall. He shall not abandon me, and I shall not abandon His will. This ye shall know, and accept.&quot; <br>
<br>
Her view was subtly different now, and she could see things as she never had before... Yet greatest of all was what she now saw in her Master. &quot;Lord Reaver Tolax, thus I place my blade at your disposal.&quot; She drew the great claymore then, placing it at the Knight's feet, the bone blade glinting dully in the light of the neon formations. <br>
<br>
The ancient knight knelt to take up the blade, and reversed it, to slice a shallow cut in his own cheek. He then righted it, and with a fluid motion, sliced the same place on the newly made Reaver... &quot;Thus our blood has been mixed, and it shall be by my blood that the servants of Innoruuk shall know thee. Now stand, sister of Darkness, and take up thine weapon.&quot; And so he reversed the blade again, offering forth the pommel of the weapon to the woman before him. <br>
<br>
She took the blade, and raised it in salute. &quot;Thus I take up my blade, and I shall not set it down until all the work of the Traitor is cleansed from this world.&quot; The woman resheathed it with an easy gesture. &quot;What is your command, my Lord?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Return to your cell, Arathena. You must rest, for the trial is most harsh. In the morn, you shall be given your mission.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As you command, my Lord.&quot; And so she walked from the hall, her head held high, the whispers of disbelief following behind...  <p>--<br>
